<!-- S1 Classical DFT -->
<section class="section" id="s1">
<div class="section-num">Section 01</div>
<h2>Classical Discrete Fourier Transform</h2>
<p>Before the quantum version, let&rsquo;s recall what the <strong>Discrete Fourier Transform</strong> does. You have N numbers and want to find the frequencies hidden inside them. Mathematically it maps a time-domain sequence to the frequency domain.</p>
<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">Classical DFT &mdash; Definition</div>
  Given x&thinsp;= (x&#x2080;,&hellip;,x&#x2099;&#x208B;&#x2081;), the DFT produces X&thinsp;= (X&#x2080;,&hellip;,X&#x2099;&#x208B;&#x2081;):
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">X&#x1D71; =</div><div class="mstep-body">(1/&radic;N) &sum;&#x2096; x&#x2096; &middot; &omega;&#x2099;&#x1D71;&#x1D48C;</div></div>
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">x&#x2096; =</div><div class="mstep-body">(1/&radic;N) &sum;&#x1D71; X&#x1D71; &middot; &omega;&#x2099;&#x207B;&#x1D71;&#x1D48C;</div></div>
    <hr class="math-sep">
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">where</div><div class="mstep-body">&omega;&#x2099; = e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;/&#x2099; is the primitive N-th root of unity</div></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Key values:</strong>
  &omega;&#x2082; = e&#x2071;&#x1D745; = <strong>-1</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;
  &omega;&#x2084; = e&#x2071;&#x1D745;/&#xB2; = <strong>j</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;
  &omega;&#x2088; = e&#x2071;&#x1D745;/&#xB4; = (1+j)/&radic;2
</div>
<h3>Matrix form</h3>
<p>The DFT is a linear map X&thinsp;= F&#x2099;&thinsp;x. Writing &omega;&thinsp;= &omega;&#x2099; for conciseness, entry (q, k) of F&#x2099; is (1/&radic;N)&omega;&#x1D71;&#x1D48C;:</p>
<div class="math-block">
  <div class="eq">
    F&#x2099; = <span class="scalar">1/&radic;N</span>
    <span class="mx"><table>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>1</td><td class="c-0">&ctdot;</td><td>1</td></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>&omega;</td><td>&omega;&sup2;</td><td class="c-0">&ctdot;</td><td>&omega;&#x207F;&#x207B;&#xB9;</td></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>&omega;&sup2;</td><td>&omega;&#x2074;</td><td class="c-0">&ctdot;</td><td>&omega;&#xB2;&#x207F;&#x207B;&#xB2;</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="c-0">&vellip;</td><td class="c-0">&vellip;</td><td class="c-0">&vellip;</td><td class="c-0">&dtdot;</td><td class="c-0">&vellip;</td></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>&omega;&#x207F;&#x207B;&#xB9;</td><td>&omega;&#xB2;&#x207F;&#x207B;&#xB2;</td><td class="c-0">&ctdot;</td><td>&omega;&#x207F;&sup2;&#x207B;&#xB2;&#x207F;</td></tr>
    </table></span>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="insight"><strong>F&#x2099; is unitary:</strong> F&#x2099;&dagger;F&#x2099; = I. Every pair of columns is orthogonal with unit norm. This is why the DFT is perfectly reversible &mdash; and why its quantum version is a valid gate.</div>
<canvas id="cvDFT" width="540" height="180"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-caption">Interactive DFT &mdash; choose a preset and watch the frequency spectrum appear.</div>
<div class="controls" style="flex-wrap:wrap;gap:0.5rem;">
  <button class="btn sm" onclick="setDFTPreset('dirac')">&delta; impulse</button>
  <button class="btn sm" onclick="setDFTPreset('constant')">constant</button>
  <button class="btn sm" onclick="setDFTPreset('cos')">cosine</button>
  <button class="btn sm" onclick="setDFTPreset('random')">random</button>
</div>
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 1.1</span><span class="ex-title">Value of &omega; for N = 8</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body"><p>&omega;&#x2088; = e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;/&#xB8;. What is its Cartesian form a + bj?</p></div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">&omega;&#x2088; &asymp;</span>
      <input class="answer-input wide" id="a11" placeholder="e.g. 0.707+0.707j">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFree('a11',['0.707+0.707j','(1+j)/sqrt2'],'f11')">Check</button>
      <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHint('h11')">hint</button>
    </div>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h11">&omega;&#x2088; = cos(&pi;/4) + j sin(&pi;/4) = 1/&radic;2 + j/&radic;2 &asymp; 0.707 + 0.707j.</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="f11"></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 1.2</span><span class="ex-title">DFT of a Dirac impulse</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body"><p>x = (1,0,0,&hellip;,0). What are all the DFT values X&#x1D71;?</p></div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">X&#x1D71; =</span>
      <input class="answer-input wide" id="a12" placeholder="same for all q">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFree('a12',['1/sqrt(n)','1/sqrtN','constant','1/√n','1/√N'],'f12')">Check</button>
      <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHint('h12')">hint</button>
    </div>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h12">X&#x1D71; = (1/&radic;N)&middot;x&#x2080;&middot;&omega;&#x2099;&#x2070; = 1/&radic;N for every q. A spike in time gives a flat constant spectrum.</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="f12"></div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- S2 Quantum QFT -->
<section class="section" id="s2">
<div class="section-num">Section 02</div>
<h2>The Quantum Fourier Transform</h2>
<p>The quantum analogue of the DFT replaces classical vectors with quantum states. Instead of transforming a list of numbers, the QFT transforms the <em>amplitudes</em> of a quantum superposition, processing all 2&#x207F; amplitudes simultaneously with only O(n&sup2;) gates.</p>
<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">QFT &mdash; Definition</div>
  Given |&psi;&#x27E9; = &sum;&#x2096; x&#x2096; |k&#x27E9;, the QFT produces |&Psi;&#x27E9; = &sum;&#x1D71; X&#x1D71; |q&#x27E9; where X&#x1D71; is the classical DFT of the amplitudes x&#x2096;:
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">Action:</div><div class="mstep-body">QFT&#x2099; |&psi;&#x27E9; = F&#x2099; |&psi;&#x27E9;</div></div>
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">On basis kets:</div><div class="mstep-body">QFT&#x2099; |k&#x27E9; = (1/&radic;N) &sum;&#x1D71;&#x208C;&#x2080;&#x207F;&#x207B;&#xB9; &omega;&#x2099;&#x1D71;&#x1D48C; |q&#x27E9;</div></div>
  </div>
  Here N = 2&#x207F; where n is the number of qubits in the register.
</div>
<div class="note-box"><strong>N must be a power of 2.</strong> With n qubits we have N = 2&#x207F; states: 2, 4, 8, 16,&hellip; This is exactly the setting of the classical Fast Fourier Transform.</div>
<h3>Why is this powerful?</h3>
<p>The QFT uses quantum superposition to process all 2&#x207F; amplitudes in a single circuit pass. Gate count: O(n&sup2;) vs classical O(N log N) = O(n&middot;2&#x207F;) &mdash; an <em>exponential</em> saving.</p>
<div class="insight"><strong>Exponential gate savings:</strong> For n&thinsp;= 1024 qubits, classical FFT needs ~10&sup3;&middot;2&#x2081;&#x2030;&#xB2;&#x2074; operations. The QFT needs only n&sup2; &asymp; 10&sup6; gates. This is the engine behind Shor&rsquo;s algorithm.</div>
<div class="ex-block">
  <div class="ex-header"><span class="ex-tag">Ex 2.1</span><span class="ex-title">QFT for N = 2</span></div>
  <div class="ex-body"><p>For N = 2 (one qubit), &omega;&#x2082; = &minus;1. Compute F&#x2082; from the matrix formula. What well-known gate is it?</p></div>
  <div class="answer-area">
    <div class="answer-row">
      <span class="ans-label">F&#x2082; =</span>
      <input class="answer-input" id="a21" placeholder="gate name" style="width:120px;">
      <button class="btn sm" onclick="chkFree('a21',['H','hadamard','h'],'f21')">Check</button>
      <button class="hint-toggle" onclick="showHint('h21')">hint</button>
    </div>
    <div class="feedback hint" id="h21">F&#x2082; = (1/&radic;2)[[1,1],[1,&omega;&#x2082;]] = (1/&radic;2)[[1,1],[1,&minus;1]] = H (Hadamard!).</div>
    <div class="feedback" id="f21"></div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- S3 QFT Circuit Derivation -->
<section class="section" id="s3">
<div class="section-num">Section 03</div>
<h2>QFT Circuit Derivation: From Formula to Gates</h2>

<p>The central insight is that the QFT output has a <strong>product structure</strong>: each output qubit can be written as a single-qubit superposition, with a phase that depends only on a few bits of the input. We will derive this from the formula, then read off the gate circuit directly from the maths.</p>

<h3>Step 1 &mdash; The product representation</h3>
<p>Any integer k between 0 and N&minus;1 can be written in binary: k&thinsp;= k&#x2080; + 2k&#x2081; + 4k&#x2082; + &hellip; + 2&#x207F;&#x207B;&#xB9;k&#x2099;&#x208B;&#x2081; where each k&#x1D62; is 0 or 1. We write the basis state as |k&#x27E9; = |k&#x2099;&#x208B;&#x2081;&hellip;k&#x2081;k&#x2080;&#x27E9;. After substituting k into the QFT formula and expanding, one finds:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--green);">Product form:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">QFT&#x2099; |k&#x27E9; = <span class="scalar">1/&radic;N</span> (|0&#x27E9; + e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;0.k&#x2080; |1&#x27E9;) &otimes; (|0&#x27E9; + e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;0.k&#x2081;k&#x2080; |1&#x27E9;) &otimes; &hellip; &otimes; (|0&#x27E9; + e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;0.k&#x2099;&#x208B;&#x2081;&hellip;k&#x2080; |1&#x27E9;)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Meaning:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Output qubit m gets superposition |0&#x27E9; + e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;(binary fraction) |1&#x27E9;. The phase for qubit m depends only on k&#x2098;, k&#x2098;&#x208B;&#x2081;, &hellip;, k&#x2080; &mdash; not all of k.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>Binary fraction notation:</strong> 0.k&#x2098;k&#x2098;&#x208B;&#x2081;&hellip;k&#x2080; = k&#x2098;/2 + k&#x2098;&#x208B;&#x2081;/4 + &hellip; + k&#x2080;/2&#x207F;. So e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;0.k&#x2080; = e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080; = (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#x2080;. If k&#x2080;&thinsp;= 0 the phase is +1; if k&#x2080;&thinsp;= 1 the phase is &minus;1. This is <em>exactly</em> what Hadamard does!
</div>

<h3>Step 2 &mdash; N = 2 (one qubit): QFT is Hadamard</h3>
<p>For n&thinsp;= 1, k&thinsp;= k&#x2080;, and the product formula gives just one factor:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">Formula:</div><div class="mstep-body">QFT&#x2082; |k&#x2080;&#x27E9; = (1/&radic;2) (|0&#x27E9; + e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080; |1&#x27E9;)</div></div>
  <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">k&#x2080; = 0:</div><div class="mstep-body">e&#x2070; = 1 &rarr; output = (|0&#x27E9;+|1&#x27E9;)/&radic;2 = |+&#x27E9;</div></div>
  <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">k&#x2080; = 1:</div><div class="mstep-body">e&#x2071;&#x1D745; = &minus;1 &rarr; output = (|0&#x27E9;&minus;|1&#x27E9;)/&radic;2 = |&minus;&#x27E9;</div></div>
  <hr class="math-sep">
  <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--green);">Gate:</div><div class="mstep-body">This is exactly H! &nbsp; H|0&#x27E9; = |+&#x27E9; and H|1&#x27E9; = |&minus;&#x27E9;. So <strong>QFT&#x2082; = H</strong>.</div></div>
</div>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="eq">F&#x2082; = <span class="scalar">1/&radic;2</span> <span class="mx"><table><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>1</td><td class="c-n">&minus;1</td></tr></table></span> = H</div>
</div>

<div class="insight"><strong>Hadamard is the 1-qubit QFT.</strong> Applying H to all n qubits in |0&#x27E9;&#x2E3E;n creates the equal superposition (1/&radic;N)&sum;|k&#x27E9; &mdash; the all-at-once input needed by frequency-domain algorithms.</div>

<h3>Step 3 &mdash; N = 4 (two qubits): deriving controlled phase gates</h3>
<p>Now k = k&#x2080; + 2k&#x2081;. The product formula gives two output qubits. Let&rsquo;s work out the circuit for each qubit separately:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label">Full output:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">QFT&#x2084; |k&#x27E9; = <span class="scalar">1/2</span> (|0&#x27E9; + e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;0.k&#x2080; |1&#x27E9;) &otimes; (|0&#x27E9; + e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;0.k&#x2081;k&#x2080; |1&#x27E9;)</div>
  </div>
  <hr class="math-sep">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--accent);">First factor:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Phase = e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080; = (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#x2080; &mdash; depends only on k&#x2080;.<br>Gate: <strong>H applied to wire k&#x2080;</strong>. Done.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--accent);">Second factor:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">Phase = e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;&middot;0.k&#x2081;k&#x2080; = e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2081; &middot; e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080;/2 = (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#xB9; &middot; e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080;/2<br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&bull; (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#xB9; part: <strong>H applied to wire k&#x2081;</strong><br>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&bull; e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080;/2 part: add phase &omega;&#x2084;&#x1D48C;&#x2080; = j&#x1D48C;&#x2080; to |1&#x27E9;, controlled by k&#x2080; &rarr; <strong>controlled-&Omega;&#x2084; gate</strong></div>
  </div>
  <hr class="math-sep">
  <div class="mstep">
    <div class="mstep-label" style="color:var(--green);">Circuit recipe:</div>
    <div class="mstep-body">1. H on wire k&#x2081; &rarr; creates (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#xB9; factor<br>2. Controlled-&Omega;&#x2084; (ctrl: k&#x2080;, target: k&#x2081; wire) &rarr; adds e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080;/2<br>3. H on wire k&#x2080; &rarr; creates (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#x2080; factor<br>4. Output in REVERSE order &rarr; add SWAP to fix.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="note-box">
  <strong>The controlled phase gate &Omega;&#x2099;:</strong> diag(1, &omega;&#x2099;) &mdash; leaves |0&#x27E9; unchanged, multiplies |1&#x27E9; by &omega;&#x2099; = e&#x2071;&#xB2;&#x1D745;/&#x2099;.
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.4rem;">
    <div class="eq">&Omega;&#x2099; = <span class="mx"><table><tr><td>1</td><td class="c-0">0</td></tr><tr><td class="c-0">0</td><td class="c-j">&omega;&#x2099;</td></tr></table></span></div>
    <div class="eq"><span class="eq-note">&Omega;&#x2084; = S gate (&omega;&#x2084;=j) &nbsp;&nbsp; &Omega;&#x2088; = T gate (&omega;&#x2088;=e&#x2071;&#x1D745;/&#xB4;) &nbsp;&nbsp; general: R&#x2082;(2&pi;/N) up to global phase</span></div>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Step 4 &mdash; N = 8 (three qubits): the staircase pattern</h3>
<p>The pattern generalises perfectly. For 3 qubits, k = k&#x2080; + 2k&#x2081; + 4k&#x2082;. Each output qubit m needs H plus a cascade of controlled phase gates with decreasing angle, controlled by lower-order bits:</p>

<div class="math-block">
  <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">Output q&#x2082; (MSB):</div><div class="mstep-body">Phase = (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#x2080; &mdash; only k&#x2080; matters. Gate: <strong>H on k&#x2080;</strong>.</div></div>
  <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">Output q&#x2081;:</div><div class="mstep-body">Phase = (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#xB9; &middot; e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080;/2. Gates: <strong>H on k&#x2081;</strong>, then <strong>ctrl-&Omega;&#x2084;</strong> from k&#x2080;.</div></div>
  <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label">Output q&#x2080; (LSB):</div><div class="mstep-body">Phase = (&minus;1)&#x1D48C;&#xB2; &middot; e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2081;/2 &middot; e&#x2071;&#x1D745;k&#x2080;/4. Gates: <strong>H on k&#x2082;</strong>, then <strong>ctrl-&Omega;&#x2084;</strong> from k&#x2081;, then <strong>ctrl-&Omega;&#x2088;</strong> from k&#x2080;.</div></div>
</div>

<div class="circuit" style="margin-top:0.8rem;">
  <div class="circuit-row">
    <span class="circuit-label">|k&#x2080;&#x27E9;</span>
    <div class="circuit-line" style="width:3rem;"></div>
    <span style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--muted);">&#x25CF;&mdash;&mdash;&#x25CF;&mdash;</span>
    <div class="circuit-gate h">H</div>
    <div class="circuit-line"></div>
    <span class="circuit-out">|q&#x2082;&#x27E9;</span>
  </div>
  <div class="circuit-row" style="margin-top:0.25rem;">
    <span class="circuit-label">|k&#x2081;&#x27E9;</span>
    <div class="circuit-line" style="width:1rem;"></div>
    <span style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--muted);">&#x25CF;&mdash;</span>
    <div class="circuit-gate h">H</div>
    <div class="circuit-gate" style="border-color:var(--orange);color:var(--orange);">&Omega;&#x2084;</div>
    <div class="circuit-line"></div>
    <span class="circuit-out">|q&#x2081;&#x27E9;</span>
  </div>
  <div class="circuit-row" style="margin-top:0.25rem;">
    <span class="circuit-label">|k&#x2082;&#x27E9;</span>
    <div class="circuit-gate h">H</div>
    <div class="circuit-gate" style="border-color:var(--orange);color:var(--orange);">&Omega;&#x2084;</div>
    <div class="circuit-gate" style="border-color:var(--green);color:var(--green);">&Omega;&#x2088;</div>
    <div class="circuit-line"></div>
    <span class="circuit-out">|q&#x2080;&#x27E9;</span>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="note-box" style="margin-top:0.8rem;">
  <strong>Recursive structure:</strong> QFT&#x2088; contains QFT&#x2084; as a sub-circuit. Each new qubit adds one H and a column of controlled phase gates. This triangular staircase means total gate count = n(n+1)/2.
</div>
<div class="insight"><strong>Output reversal:</strong> The product formula outputs q&#x2099;&#x208B;&#x2081;&hellip;q&#x2080; in reverse order. In many algorithms this reversal is absorbed into downstream connections, so explicit SWAP gates are often omitted.</div>

